    <h1 id="header-text">
        IMPROPER SORTING OF <span>RECYCLING MATERIALS</span>
    </h1>
    <p>
        Improper sorting happens when non-recyclable items or contaminated materials are placed in recycling bins. This can result in:
    </p>
    <ul type="disc">
        <li><h3>Contamination of Recyclables:</h3>A single greasy pizza box or a dirty food container can ruin an entire batch of paper or plastics, making them unusable for recycling.</li>
        <li><h3>Equipment Damage:</h3>Non-recyclable items like plastic bags or wires can tangle recycling machinery, causing breakdowns and expensive repairs.</li>
        <li><h3>Increased Waste:</h3>Materials that are incorrectly sorted often get sent to landfills, negating recycling efforts and increasing environmental strain.</li>
    </ul>
    <h1 style="text-align: center; padding-top: 1%;">
        How to Avoid Improper Sorting:
    </h1>
    <ul type="disc">
        <li><h3>Know your local rules: </h3>Recycling guidelines vary. Check what materials are accepted in your area.</li>
        <li><h3>Rinse and clean</h3>Wash containers to remove food residue.</li>
        <li><h3>Avoid Wish-Cycling</h3>Don’t toss in items you hope are recyclable. When in doubt, leave it out.</li>
    </ul>
